Here's a simple example of a JavaScript event listener that updates the DOM when a button is clicked:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
    <button id="myButton">Click Me</button>
    <p id="output">Initial text</p>

    <script>
        // Select the button and output elements
        const button = document.getElementById('myButton');
        const outputElement = document.getElementById('output');

        // Add click event listener to the button
        button.addEventListener('click', function() {
            // Update the text content when button is clicked
            outputElement.textContent = 'Button was clicked!';

            // Optionally, you can also change styles
            outputElement.style.color = 'red';
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

Here's a slightly more advanced version with multiple ways to modify the DOM:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
    <button id="incrementBtn">Increment</button>
    <p id="counterDisplay">Count: 0</p>

    <script>
        // Initialize a counter
        let count = 0;

        // Select the button and display elements
        const incrementButton = document.getElementById('incrementBtn');
        const counterDisplay = document.getElementById('counterDisplay');

        // Add click event listener
        incrementButton.addEventListener('click', function() {
            // Increment the counter
            count++;

            // Update the text content
            counterDisplay.textContent = `Count: ${count}`;

            // Change background color based on count
            if (count % 2 === 0) {
                counterDisplay.style.backgroundColor = 'lightblue';
            } else {
                counterDisplay.style.backgroundColor = 'lightgreen';
            }

            // Optional: Add a console log
            console.log(`Button clicked. New count: ${count}`);
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

If you prefer using an arrow function:

```javascript
button.addEventListener('click', () => {
    outputElement.textContent = 'Button clicked with arrow function!';
});
```

Key points:
- `addEventListener()` is used to attach the event listener
- `click` is the event type
- The function passed is the event handler
- `document.getElementById()` selects DOM elements
- You can modify `textContent`, `innerHTML`, `style`, etc.

For multiple elements or more complex scenarios:

```javascript
// Select all buttons with a specific class
const buttons = document.querySelectorAll('.action-btn');

// Add event listener to each button
buttons.forEach(button => {
    button.addEventListener('click', function() {
        // Do something for each button
        console.log('Button clicked:', this.textContent);
    });
});
```

These examples demonstrate basic DOM manipulation and event handling in JavaScript. Choose the approach that best fits your specific use case.

