Here's a clean, modern approach to adding an event listener in JavaScript:

```typescript
// Recommended: Use querySelector to select the button
const button = document.querySelector('#myButton');

// Add event listener with arrow function
button?.addEventListener('click', (event: Event) => {
  // Prevent default button behavior if needed
  event.preventDefault();

  // Example: Update DOM element text
  const targetElement = document.querySelector('#targetElement');
  if (targetElement) {
    targetElement.textContent = 'Button was clicked!';
  }

  // Optional: Add a class for styling
  targetElement?.classList.add('clicked');
});
```

Best practices demonstrated:
- Use `querySelector` for element selection
- Optional chaining (`?.`) to prevent null errors
- Type annotation for event
- Check for element existence before manipulation
- Prevent default behavior if necessary
- Use arrow function for concise syntax

Alternatively, with more robust error handling:

```typescript
function initializeButtonListener() {
  const button = document.getElementById('myButton');
  const target = document.getElementById('targetElement');

  if (!button || !target) {
    console.error('Required elements not found');
    return;
  }

  button.addEventListener('click', (event: Event) => {
    try {
      target.textContent = `Clicked at ${new Date().toLocaleTimeString()}`;
    } catch (error) {
      console.error('Error updating element:', error);
    }
  });
}

// Call when DOM is ready
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', initializeButtonListener);
```

This version adds:
- Error checking for element existence
- Try/catch for error handling
- DOMContentLoaded event to ensure elements exist
- More descriptive logging

Choose the approach that best fits your specific use case.
